# Project Rules for Cline

Follow every rule below on every task. These exist to compensate for the failure modes of smaller models — skipping steps is what causes broken code, not slowness.

---

## 1. Before writing any code

- Restate the task in your own words in one sentence before starting, to confirm you understood it.
- List every file you will create or touch. Do not touch files outside this list without saying why.
- If the task is ambiguous or could be done multiple ways, pick the simplest interpretation and state the assumption — don't ask, don't overbuild.
- Break the task into small steps (aim for steps you could each finish in under ~20 lines of change). Work through them one at a time, not all at once.

## 2. Structure and scope

- Keep HTML, CSS, and JS in ONE file unless told otherwise. Fewer files = fewer places for things to get out of sync.
- <style> goes in <head>. <script> goes immediately before </body> (never in <head> without defer).
- Do not add features, libraries, error handling, or abstractions that weren't asked for. Extra surface area is extra chances to break something.
- Prefer plain vanilla HTML/CSS/JS. Only reach for a framework or library if explicitly requested.
- Do not refactor or "clean up" unrelated code while doing a specific task, unless asked.

## 3. Naming consistency (the #1 cause of broken sites)

- Before writing JS, list every element ID/class the JS will reference.
- After writing the HTML, check each one exists with identical spelling and case. Do this explicitly — don't assume.
- Never reference an element in JS that wasn't just written in the HTML in this same response.
- Use consistent naming conventions throughout (e.g. don't mix checkboxItem and checkbox-item).

## 4. Every interactive element must actually work

- Any button, checkbox, tab, link, or form must have a real event listener attached to a real function — not just a function defined and left unattached.
- After writing the JS, trace each interactive HTML element to the specific line of JS that gives it behavior. If you can't point to that line, it's not done.
- Test state changes mentally: what does the DOM look like before the click, and after? If nothing would visibly change, the logic is wrong.

## 5. Defensive basics (cheap insurance against silent failures)

- Guard DOM lookups where it matters: if (el) { ... } before using an element, so a mismatch throws a clear console error instead of failing silently.
- Never assume getElementById/querySelector succeeded.
- Avoid !important, inline styles, and global variables unless there's a specific reason — they hide bugs and cause conflicts as the file grows.

## 6. Self-check before ending any response

Run through this list explicitly before finishing — don't skip it because the code "looks right":

- [ ] Every ID/class in JS matches the HTML exactly
- [ ] Every clickable/checkable/interactive element has a listener actually wired to it
- [ ] Script tag is at the end of <body> or uses defer
- [ ] No placeholder or unused functions left in the code
- [ ] No console errors would occur on page load (trace through it mentally)
- [ ] The feature actually does what was asked, not just something adjacent to it

## 7. When fixing a bug

- Ask for the exact browser console error or the specific symptom before guessing at a fix. Don't rewrite broadly to "be safe."
- Change only what's needed to fix the reported issue.
- After the fix, re-run the Section 6 self-check.
- If the same type of bug happens twice in a session, say so explicitly and slow down — re-verify the whole file rather than patching again.

## 8. Incremental delivery

- For anything beyond a single simple page, build and verify one section/feature at a time rather than generating the whole thing in one pass.
- After each meaningful chunk, pause and re-check Section 6 before moving to the next chunk.
- If a task feels like it's getting complex (more than ~3-4 interactive features, or multiple pages), say so and suggest breaking it into separate requests.

## 9. Communication

- If something in the request can't be done simply, say so plainly instead of producing a half-working version.
- Don't claim something is "done" or "should work now" without having gone through the Section 6 checklist first.
- If you're not confident in a piece of logic, flag it rather than presenting it as certain.

## 10. Know the limits

- This project intentionally avoids complexity (no build tools, no frameworks, no backend) specifically to stay within what a smaller model can reliably verify by hand.
- If a request would require holding a lot of interacting state or logic in your head at once, that's a signal to simplify the approach, not to push through.

"When using Ollama, always assume OLLAMA_FLASH_ATTENTION=1 is enabled and use a num_ctx of 16384 for all operations to ensure stability with my 32GB RAM limit."